applicationInfo.name: AWS Connected Vehicle Solution
applicationInfo.description:
The AWS Connected Vehicle Solution for fleet management is an imaginary system that the exercises in this workshop are based on.

![](https://static.us-east-1.prod.workshops.aws/public/34368bf8-0bc7-47b7-9611-3620bfbfb1c1/static/connected-vehicle-solution.png)

There are a number of functions and capabilities within this system, including:

- Internet of Things (IoT) connected vehicles
- Vehicle registration
- Driver registration
- Capturing diagnostic error codes
- Sending trip data from connected vehicles to the AWS solution

This telemetry data is pushed through analytics tools for anomaly detection, which provides ongoing assurance that the vehicles operate within their baseline norms and drivers adhere to traffic regulations.

Like many real-world scenarios, this is a rather complex system.

architecture.description:
[Vehicle registration feture](https://catalog.workshops.aws/threatmodel/en-US/what-are-we-working-on/exercise/vehicle-registration-feature#included-in-the-architecture)

The vehicle registration feature is the decomposed portion of the AWS Connected Vehicle Solution that you will threat model. To recap, it aims to address this user story:

“As a vehicle fleet manager, I want to register an existing IoT connected vehicle to bring it into service.”

This feature builds upon those that have already been threat modeled and deployed, namely the web front-end hosted on AWS Amplify and user authentication through Amazon Cognito.I[ncluded in the architecture](https://catalog.workshops.aws/threatmodel/en-US/what-are-we-working-on/exercise/vehicle-registration-feature#included-in-the-architecture)

- The existing AWS Amplify deployment for the required static assets to render the webpage (HTML, JavaScript, and CSS); and
- The existing Amazon Cognito integration for user pool authentication.

[API support](https://catalog.workshops.aws/threatmodel/en-US/what-are-we-working-on/exercise/vehicle-registration-feature#api-support)

The vehicle registration backend will support the following APIs:

- **ListVehicles** Returns information for all available IoT-connected vehicles.
- **RegisterVehicle** Registers an existing IoT-connected vehicle to bring it into service. Registration inputs include registration number, expiry, and vehicle registration in PDF.
- **DeregisterVehicle** Deregisters an existing registered IoT-connected vehicle to bring out of service. Deregistration will remove registration number and expiry and delete the vehicle registration in PDF.
- **DescribeVehicle** Returns information for a specific IoT-connected vehicle, including a [_presigned URL_ ](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/ShareObjectPreSignedURL.html)
- to the vehicle registration in PDF.

Furthermore, the design of this feature will require object storage and retrieval since the vehicle registration in PDF, supplied by the user, will be:

- Passed to the RegisterVehicle API,
- Stored in an Amazon S3 Bucket,
- Retrievable through the DescribeVehicle API, and
- Deleted through the DeregisterVehicle API.

Each API call will return a Globally Unique ID (GUID).

[Amazon S3 Bucket](https://catalog.workshops.aws/threatmodel/en-US/what-are-we-working-on/exercise/vehicle-registration-feature#amazon-s3-bucket)

- As part of the baseline security requirements that your organization has defined, the Amazon S3 Bucket uses [_server-side encryption_ ](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/serv-side-encryption.html)
- With this, Amazon S3 encrypts your data at the object level as it writes it to disks in its data centers and decrypts it for you when you access it.

dataflow.description: Here's a reference DFD for the Vehicle Registration Feature.

assumptions.content: The Amazon API Gateway and AWS Lambda function are within the same trust zone; therefore, the Lambda function trusts that requests originating from the API Gateway are already authenticated. Additional authentication is not performed by the Lambda function code.
RegisterVehicle: uploaded PDF documents are not being parsed by any custom code; the bytes are simply being written to S3.
There is a single authorization scope, which allows access and interactions with all listed APIs: ListVehicles, RegisterVehicle, DeregisterVehicle, and DescribeVehicle.
The system design will align to the AWS Well-Architected Security Pillar.
We will use S3 encryption at rest.
We will use DynamoDB encryption at rest.
Lambda API endpoints only support secure connections over HTTPS.
Web browser to the API Gateway is protected by TLS.
Amplify, Cognito, and the API Gateway are also used for the driver registration feature.
There is a single S3 bucket.
There is a single DynamoDB table.
A single Lambda function is supporting all of the APIs.
AWS services in this diagram are in the same AWS account.
AWS services in this diagram are in the same region.
The web browser is patched and up to date.
All users can perform all operations.
REST-based APIs are served by AWS Lambda and the Amazon API Gateway.
MFA is not used by users

mitigations.content: Perform vulnerability management
Use detective controls to identify potential security threats or incidents.
Throttle API requests
Set up Lambda integrations in API Gateway
Detect unexpected or unwanted configuration changes, and detect unexpected behavior
Use AWS Web Application Firewall and AWS Shield
Use Amazon Macie to discover and protect your sensitive data
Use strong sign-in mechanisms
Use Cognito to authenticate users
Limit pre-signed S3 URL capabilities
Use IAM security best practices   to manage access to your AWS account and resources
Use Cognito and API Gateway to authorize users
Automate testing and validation of security controls
Back up your data
Protect your data at rest
Manage access to critical resources   and apply least-privilege permissions
Use AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) to provision, manage, and deploy public and private SSL/TLS certificates
Validate All Inputs  : “Input validation is a programming technique that ensures only properly formatted data may enter a software system component."
Use AWS monitoring and logging
Protect Sensitive Data with Amazon CloudWatch Logs
Configure API Gateway API Responses   to return appropriate information only
Protect data-in-transit
Monitor cost proactively

threats.prerequisites: with access to the AWS account
threats.threatAction: deploy a lambda function that will use existing execution role
threats.statement: An internal actor with access to the AWS account can deploy a lambda function that will use existing execution role, which leads to unauthorised access to sensitive data, resulting in reduced confidentiality of registration status

threats.prerequisites: with knowledge of employee email addresses
threats.threatImpact: unauthorized access to Vehicle Registration System
threats.statement: An external threat actor with knowledge of employee email addresses can password spray Cognito, which leads to unauthorized access to Vehicle Registration System, resulting in reduced confidentiality of vehicle registration documents

threats.prerequisites: with access to modify network traffic
threats.threatImpact: the API Gateway performing actions on another user's resources
threats.statement: A threat actor with access to modify network traffic can manipulate API parameter input which leads to the API Gateway performing actions on another user's resources, resulting in reduced integrity and confidentiality of vehicle registration, vehicle listing, registration status, and vehicle registration documents.

threats.prerequisites: with access to an IAM Principal with modify access to the S3 bucket
threats.threatAction: cause data in the Amazon S3 bucket to be deleted
threats.threatImpact: cause data in the Amazon S3 bucket to be deleted
threats.statement: A threat actor with access to an IAM Principal with modify access to the S3 bucket can cause data in the Amazon S3 bucket to be deleted, resulting in reduced availability of vehicle registration documents.

threats.prerequisites: with access to an IAM Principal with modify access to the DynamoDB tables
threats.statement: A threat actor with access to an IAM Principal with modify access to the DynamoDB tables can delete the data, resulting in reduced availability of vehicle registration, vehicle listing, and registration status.

threats.prerequisites: who is able to access the AWS Lambda function logs
threats.threatAction: find sensitive data captured within the logs
threats.threatImpact: find sensitive data captured within the logs
threats.statement: A threat actor who is able to access the AWS Lambda function logs can find sensitive data captured within the logs, resulting in reduced confidentiality of vehicle registration, vehicle listing, registration status, and vehicle registration documents.

threats.threatAction: make API requests can read information they should not be authorized to read
threats.threatImpact: make API requests can read information they should not be authorized to read
threats.statement: A threat actor who is authenticated and can make API requests can read information they should not be authorized to read, resulting in reduced confidentiality of vehicle registration, vehicle listing, registration status, and vehicle registration documents.

threats.threatAction: register a vehicle can claim they did not do so
threats.threatImpact: the actor disputing financial charges related to the registration of a vehicle
threats.statement: A threat actor who can register a vehicle can claim they did not do so which leads to the actor disputing financial charges related to the registration of a vehicle, resulting in reduced integrity of billing.

threats.prerequisites: with access to data in transit between the user and the Amazon S3 bucket
threats.statement: A threat actor with access to data in transit between the user and the Amazon S3 bucket can read or modify that data, resulting in reduced confidentiality and/or integrity of vehicle registration documents.

threats.prerequisites: who is able to access the DynamoDB tables
threats.statement: A threat actor who is able to access the DynamoDB tables can access sensitive data, which leads to unauthorized access, resulting in reduced confidentiality of vehicle registration, vehicle listing and registration status

threats.prerequisites: with possession of a similar domain name
threats.threatAction: trick our users into interacting with a fake endpoint
threats.statement: A threat actor with possession of a similar domain name can trick our users into interacting with a fake endpoint, which leads to interception of valid API requests, negatively impacting vehicle registration, vehicle listing, registration status and vehicle registration documents
